# Git One-Page Cheat Sheet

Ultra-compact reference for daily development and interviews.

## 1) Setup

git --version                          # Verify Git installation
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
git config --global init.defaultBranch main

## 2) Start Work

git clone <repo-url>                  # Copy remote repo
git switch -c feature/<name>          # Create and switch to feature branch
git status                             # Check current state

## 3) Save Work

git add .                              # Stage all changes
git commit -m "feat: message"         # Commit staged changes
git push -u origin feature/<name>      # First push and set upstream

## 4) Sync Safely

git fetch --all --prune                # Download updates only
git rebase origin/main                 # Rebase feature on latest main
# Alternative:
# git pull origin main                 # Fetch + merge

## 5) Remote Commands

git remote -v
git remote add origin <repo-url>
git remote set-url origin <new-url>

Common fix (origin already exists):
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/harishmsgit/Container-Orchestration-Scaling.git

## 6) Undo and Recovery

git restore --staged <file>            # Unstage file
git restore <file>                     # Discard unstaged file edits
git reset --soft HEAD~1                # Undo last commit, keep changes
git reflog                             # Recover lost commit references

Danger zone:
git reset --hard HEAD~1                # Deletes local tracked changes

## 7) Stash for Interruptions

git stash push -m "wip: note"
git stash list
git stash pop

## 8) Branch Cleanup

git branch -d <branch>                 # Delete merged local branch
git push origin --delete <branch>      # Delete remote branch

## 9) Merge and Rebase Conflict Flow

During rebase conflict:
1. Fix files
2. git add <resolved-file>
3. git rebase --continue
4. If needed: git rebase --abort

During merge conflict:
1. Fix files
2. git add <resolved-file>
3. git merge --continue
4. If needed: git merge --abort

## 10) Interview Quick Recall

- fetch vs pull: fetch only downloads; pull downloads and integrates.
- merge vs rebase: merge preserves branch structure; rebase creates linear history.
- reflog is the recovery safety net.
- prefer small commits with clear commit messages.

## 11) 30-Second Daily Routine

1. git status
2. git fetch --all --prune
3. git rebase origin/main
4. git add .
5. git commit -m "type: concise message"
6. git push -u origin feature/<name>

## 12) Requested Commands

Undo last commit (choose based on need):

git reset --soft HEAD~1                # Undo commit, keep code staged
git reset --mixed HEAD~1               # Undo commit, keep code unstaged
git reset --hard HEAD~1                # Undo commit, delete local changes

If last commit was already pushed and you want safe undo:

git revert HEAD                         # Create new commit that reverses last commit

If you want to overwrite remote history (careful):

git reset --hard HEAD~1
git push --force-with-lease origin <branch>

Cherry-pick a particular commit:

git log --oneline                       # Find required commit hash
git switch <target-branch>
git cherry-pick <commit-hash>

Cherry-pick multiple commits:

git cherry-pick a1b2c3d e4f5g6h 9a0b1c2

Real example:
git switch release/v1.2.0
git cherry-pick 3f91a2b 8c74d10 b5e6f33

Cherry-pick a commit range:

git cherry-pick 4d2a1f0^..7b8c9d1

Real example:
git switch hotfix/login-errors
git cherry-pick 21ac9f4^..5e7bd32

If cherry-pick gets conflicts:

git status
git add backend/authService/controllers/user.controller.js
git add frontend/src/pages/Login.js
git cherry-pick --continue
# If needed:
# git cherry-pick --abort
